node.text:
After not checking our mailboxes for several months, we had a ton of fan mail to catch up on!💌✨

Happy Thanksgiving from the Astronaut Corps! Enjoy the 2020 edition of astronauts reading fan mail featuring Anne McClain, @astrodrewmorgan, @astro_jessica, @jonnykimUSA, @astro_jeanette, @astromarshburn, and Mike Fincke.

node.text:
Space Anchor @astro_seal is here to deliver Some Space News🌠⁣⁣
⁣⁣
There are lots of dynamic operations on @iss this week, and there’s more to come with the awaited arrival of @astro.doug & Bob Behnken on the @spacex Crew Dragon vehicle. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Stay tuned for more space news & watch #LaunchAmerica May 30 at 3:22pm ET!

node.text:
⁣
Do you have pencils in space? What food do you eat? How do you say astronaut in Russian?✏️👨‍🚀🍤⁣ ⁣⁣
⁣
In the spirit of Thanksgiving, our astronauts took time to answer some of your burning questions from fan mail they received.
⁣
#HappyThanksgiving to all, we’re thankful for YOU!
⁣
Special thank you to the following astronauts for sharing their favorite letters and answering questions: @astro_seal, @jeanette.epps, @astrohague, @zenanaut, Tracy Caldwell Dyson, and Reid Wiseman.

node.text:
⁣
Today’s #FunFactFriday shouldn’t come as a surprise…⁣⁣
⁣⁣
@astro_christina and @astro_jessica made history today when they conducted the first all-female spacewalk. This was the first spacewalk of Meir’s career, and the fourth for Koch.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The two astronauts joined a long list of trailblazers, both male and female, marking significant milestones in spacewalk history.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Watch the full video for bonus fun facts!🌟

node.text:
Hungry? Let’s taco bout it! 🌮

Space food has evolved a lot since our early missions. Our astronauts use a hydration station to prepare their dried space food and drinks! 

The juice comes in a powder that just needs water added to it just like we do here on earth! 

The food comes packaged in a vacuum sealed baggy with an opening for a needle to hydrate the various foods that are sent on resupply missions. These foods include fruits, nuts, seafood, eggs, beef, candy, crackers, and peanut butter to name a few.

After hydrating their food, the astronauts have the option of eating hot or cold by either putting it in the 
warming oven or in the fridge.

What comfort foods would you want to eat in space?

node.text:
Happy Veggie Harvest Anniversary!🌱

Six years ago, today on August 10th, NASA astronaut @astro_kjell and former astronaut @stationcdrkelly harvested and ate the first successful full crop of lettuce on the @iss.

Here are some interesting facts about the veggie system:

• The Veggie concept is a simple, low-power system to grow fresh, nutritious food for our astronauts to supplement their diet and use as a tool to support relaxation and recreation.

• It runs on about 70 watts for the lights, fans, and control electronics.
 
• Veggie utilizes passive wicking to provide water to the plants as they grow.

• There are two Veggie units aboard the station, along with a more sophisticated growth chamber, the Advanced Plant Habitat.

Over the last six years, NASA astronauts have now grown a variety of plants, including three types of 
lettuce, Chinese cabbage, mizuna mustard, red Russian kale, and zinnia flowers. 

Research like this will help @nasa understand how to keep plants flourishing in space and better enable long-duration missions like @nasaartemis.

node.text:
✨Happy #nationalinternday! ✨

We like to recognize the achievements of all our astronauts and in doing so, it’s important to recognize where it all started. Did you know that some of our @NASA astronauts started out having @NASAinternships? 📝

Loral O’Hara: Loral’s first NASA experience was when her second-grade class grew tomato 🍅 plants from seeds that were flown on the space shuttle. This sparked her interest in aviation and her dreams of becoming an astronaut. 👨‍🚀 Following her second-grade experience, she found herself studying aerospace engineering in college and landed an internship at @NASAJPL, teaching her about flight hardware and paving the way for her success as an astronaut for NASA!

Jessica Watkins: @astro_watkins’s undergraduate internships at NASA consisted of research on the 
Phoenix Mars Lander mission. After becoming a graduate student, she began various internships and research projects at @NASAJPL. By the time she finished her graduate program 👩‍🎓 she had multiple years of experience researching with NASA and it opened the door for her to become an astronaut!

Warren “Woody” Hoburg: @whoburg is another one of our astronauts that started out his astronaut 
career as an intern for NASA. He studied Aeronautics and Astronautics for his undergraduate degree and landed a summer internship at @NASAJPL, working on Mars Science Laboratory, studying how dust from the descent-stage thrusters might affect the rover landing. His internship experience at NASA enabled him to rocket 🚀 his career forward as an astronaut! 👩‍🚀

#NASAInterns #NASAInternships #STEM #STEMinternships #NASA #Astronaut #NASAastronauts

#OTD 60 years ago, Alan Shepard made history when he climbed aboard the Freedom 7 capsule atop a Redstone rocket and became the first American to fly in space. 

More on Alan Shepard’s legendary astronaut career...

🧑‍🚀 Selected as one of NASA’s first seven astronauts in 1959. 

🚀 Became the first American in space in 1961 on the historic Mercury-Redstone 3 Mission.

🌙 Walked on the moon in 1971 during the Apollo 14 Mission, where he not only conducted important science, but also became the first person to hit a golf ball on the moon.

#astronaut #nasa #alanshepard #60thanniversary #nationalastronautday

✔️ Mission complete!

After 168 days in space, NASA’s SpaceX Crew-1 astronauts arrived home on May 2. 

In the most fitting fashion, their mission, which certified the return of astronaut launches from the U.S., ended with an equally historic moonlit splashdown at 2:56am ET in the Gulf of Mexico. 

To learn more about the Crew-1 Mission check out the link in our bio!

Photo credit: NASA/@ingallsimages

2 dragons and 11 humans are in space👩‍🚀🐉💫

On Saturday Crew-2 successfully docked to the @iss, making the current population of humans in space go from 7 to 11 until Crew-1 returns to Earth in a few days. 

#LaunchAmerica

node.text:
3...2...1...liftoff🚀

Crew-2 astronauts successfully launched from @nasakennedy at 5:49 a.m. ET this morning and are making their way to the @iss! Docking is scheduled at 5:10 a.m. ET, Sat., April 24. Tune in to see the Space Station family go from 7 to 11 inhabitants. #LaunchAmerica

node.text: What do we miss when we're living in space? The warmth of the sun on our faces, the softness of the sand, the sweet scent of grass, and the rhythm of the rain. As we continue to explore our solar system, we can’t help but look back in awe. Happy #EarthDay to our favorite planet. #ConnectedByEarth 🌎
